  "text": "The xDS configuration discovery service flow traces how Envoy receives dynamic configuration from a control plane through a gRPC streaming mechanism:\n\n## 1. Protocol Definition (Data Plane API)\n\nThe control plane and data plane communication is defined in protobuf files in the `data-plane-api` repository. The core message types are defined in `envoy/api/v2/discovery.proto` (legacy v2) and `envoy/service/discovery/v3/discovery.proto` (current v3):\n- **DiscoveryRequest**: Sent by Envoy to request resources (includes node info, resource names, version info, type_url)\n- **DiscoveryResponse**: Sent by the control plane with versioned resources, nonce for ACK/NACK\n- **DeltaDiscoveryRequest/Response**: Incremental variants for efficient partial updates\n\nThe **AggregatedDiscoveryService** is defined in `envoy/service/discovery/v2/ads.proto` (v2) and `envoy/service/discovery/v3/ads.proto` (v3), which provides two gRPC RPCs:\n- **StreamAggregatedResources**: Bidirectional stream for state-of-the-world xDS\n- **DeltaAggregatedResources**: Bidirectional stream for incremental xDS updates\n\n## 2. Control Plane Server (Go Control Plane)\n\nThe `go-control-plane` repository provides the server-side implementation:\n- **envoy/api/v2/discovery.pb.go** and **envoy/service/discovery/v3/discovery.pb.go**: Generated Go protocol buffer bindings\n- **envoy/service/discovery/v3/ads_grpc.pb.go**: Generated gRPC service stubs with AggregatedDiscoveryServiceServer interface\n- **pkg/server/v3/server.go**: The actual server implementation that:\n  - Implements **StreamAggregatedResources()**: Handles incoming gRPC streams from Envoy clients\n  - Calls **StreamHandler()**: Routes requests to the appropriate xDS handler (sotw, delta, or rest)\n  - Sends DiscoveryResponse messages back to clients\n\n## 3. Data Plane Client (Envoy C++)\n\nEnvoy's data plane uses these key components in `source/extensions/config_subscription/grpc/`:\n\n**GrpcSubscriptionImpl** (`grpc_subscription_impl.h`/`.cc`):\n- Wraps the generic GrpcMux with configuration-specific callbacks\n- **start()**: Initiates subscription by registering a watch on the GrpcMux\n- **updateResourceInterest()**: Updates the set of subscribed resources\n- **onConfigUpdate()**: Callback invoked when the control plane sends DiscoveryResponse\n- Manages per-resource-type version tracking and statistics\n\n**GrpcMuxImpl** (`xds_mux/grpc_mux_impl.h`):\n- Multiplexes multiple resource types (LDS, CDS, RDS, EDS) onto a single ADS gRPC stream\n- Maintains a WatchMap tracking all subscribed resources\n- Batches subscription requests and ACKs them with appropriate nonces\n- Manages connection state and failover\n\n**GrpcStream** (`grpc_stream.h`):\n- Low-level gRPC stream management\n- Sends DiscoveryRequest messages (or DeltaDiscoveryRequest for delta xDS)\n- Receives DiscoveryResponse (or DeltaDiscoveryResponse)\n- Handles gRPC reconnection and rate limiting\n\n**Subscription State Management** (`xds_mux/sotw_subscription_state.h`, `xds_mux/delta_subscription_state.h`):\n- **SotwSubscriptionState**: Tracks server-sent resources for state-of-the-world xDS\n- **DeltaSubscriptionState**: Tracks per-resource versions for incremental updates\n- Generates appropriate DiscoveryRequest messages based on subscriptions and ACKs\n\n## Configuration Update Flow\n\n1. Envoy subsystems (LDS, CDS, RDS, EDS) create GrpcSubscriptionImpl instances\n2. When subscription starts, GrpcSubscriptionImpl.start() registers a watch with GrpcMux\n3. GrpcMux batches all subscriptions and sends an initial DiscoveryRequest over the ADS stream\n4. Control plane's StreamAggregatedResources() handler (in go-control-plane) receives the request\n5. Server matches the requested resources and sends back a DiscoveryResponse with versioned resources\n6. GrpcStream receives the DiscoveryResponse\n7. Subscription state machine unmarshals the resources and calls GrpcSubscriptionImpl.onConfigUpdate()\n8. The callback propagates configuration to the target subsystem (e.g., RouteConfigProvider)\n9. Envoy ACKs by sending a new DiscoveryRequest with the response nonce and matching version_info\n10. Control plane uses the nonce to correlate the ACK and track configuration acceptance\n\nThe mux design allows Envoy to receive multiple resource types over a single gRPC stream while maintaining independent version tracking and ACK/NACK semantics per resource type."
